    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div xml:id="KT393-kilavi">
                <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi alar malivu varaitta varaivu
                    kaṭāyatu. </p>


                <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante inquiring about marriage,
                    uttering joy about the gossip, while HE is behind the hedge. </p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="KT393">
                <lg type="edition">
                    <l> mayaṅkumalark kōtai kuḻaiya makiḻnaṉ</l>
                    <l> muyaṅkiya nāṭavac cilavē yalarē</l>
                    <l> kūkaik kōḻi vākaip paṟantalaip</l>
                    <l> pacumpūṭ pāṇṭiyaṉ viṉaiva latikaṉ</l>
                    <l> kaḷiṟoṭu paṭṭa ñāṉṟai</l>
                    <l> yoḷiṟuvāṭ koṅka rārppiṉum peritē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <l> Very few [were] the days the delightful man embraced [me],</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> for the garland of intertwined blossoms to soften.</l>
                    <l rend="indent9"> The gossip,</l>
                    <l> it [is] louder than the roaring of the Koṅkars with bright swords,</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> when the energetic Atikaṉ, the Pāṇṭiya with green ornaments <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">pacum pūṇ</term> is explained by T.V.G. as referring
                        to a special kind of gold, called "green gold".</note> ,</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> fell with the elephant bull,</l>
                    <l rend="indent3"> in the desert place of Vākai [full of] owls [and] fowl <note place="foot">What is a <term xml:lang="ta">kūkai kōḻi</term>? Different
                        owl-like birds? A statement to the effect that there are owls in the Sirissa
                        trees in the desert place where the armies meet would be just as well as
                        that they are in the place <term xml:lang="ta">Vākai</term> . T.V.G.
                        explains that owls and forest fowl come to devour the dead on the
                        battlefield, which is a recurrent topos in <term xml:lang="ta">Puṟam </term>
                        too (cf. PN 238.3 and 364.12).</note> .</l>


                </lg>
            </div>
        </body>
